\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door stops mid-way or reverses without hitting the floor.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Scraping or grinding sounds during movement.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Uneven travel where one side moves faster than the other.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clear debris and dirt with a soft brush or cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect for small objects or minor bends.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Gently straighten minor bends using a rubber mallet. Never forcefully.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate rollers with silicone spray, avoiding the tracks themselves.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nFor severely bent tracks, repeated misalignment, or doors that come off the tracks, call Clark &amp; Sons technicians for professional realignment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Misaligned or Blocked Safety Sensors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nGarage doors have safety sensors to prevent accidents. They stop the door if something blocks the beam. If the sensors are misaligned, dirty, or loose, the door will refuse to close. Wiring can degrade, especially in older systems, preventing proper communication with the opener.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door reverses before reaching the floor.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door won\\u2019t move at all.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Sensor lights are dim, flickering, or off.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPersistent issues or damaged wiring should be handled by a technician to prevent accidents.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Broken or Worn Springs\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSprings balance the weight of the garage door. Torsion springs above the door or extension springs along the tracks allow smooth opening and closing. If they break or weaken, the door becomes heavy, difficult to control, or won\\u2019t move at all.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door closes unevenly, or one side lags.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Loud bangs or popping sounds.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door slams or stops abruptly.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Why DIY is risky:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSprings store enormous tension. Even slight mishandling can cause serious injury or property damage.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nOur trained technician will replace or adjust springs, ensuring proper tension and safe operation. They also inspect cables and drums during spring replacement to prevent related failures.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Malfunctioning Garage Door Opener\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nThe <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/residential\\/openers\\/\\\"><b>garage door opener<\\/b><\\/a> is the motor that drives the door. Motors wear out over time, especially in high-use systems. Chain or belt drives may loosen, gears can wear, and electrical components can fail.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door moves slowly, jerks, or stops midway.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door responds inconsistently to remote or wall control.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Unusual grinding, whining, or humming noises.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPersistent issues, unusual motor sounds, or partial movement usually indicate worn gears or motor failure. Technicians can replace parts or the entire opener to restore reliable operation.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Worn or Damaged Rollers\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRollers guide the door along the tracks. Over time, plastic rollers wear, steel rollers can rust, and bearings can seize. Misaligned rollers increase friction and strain the opener.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door sticks or shakes during movement.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Loud squeaking or grinding noises.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Uneven or partial closure.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nReplace rollers if damaged. Professionals ensure proper installation and alignment, which prevents noise, uneven movements, and premature opener wear.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Cable or Pulley Problems\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nCables lift the door while pulleys guide them. Frayed cables or misaligned pulleys disrupt smooth operation.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door closes unevenly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>One side of the door lags.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Sudden jerks or binding mid-travel.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nOnly a trained technician should replace or re-tension cables. Improper handling can result in dangerous door failure.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Door Off-Track\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nGarage doors can derail from their tracks due to impact, worn hardware, or misalignment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Door jams or tilts during closing.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Stops mid-way or doesn\\u2019t move at all.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Visible gaps between the door and track.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nStop using the door immediately. A technician will safely realign tracks and reposition the door, preventing serious accidents.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Preventive Maintenance for Smooth Closing\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRegular maintenance reduces the risk of your garage door refusing to close.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Maintenance Checklist:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate hinges, rollers, springs, and bearings every 6 months.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Clean tracks and remove debris.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect and tighten hardware: bolts, brackets, and screws.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Test and clean safety sensors monthly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Perform a balance test: disconnect the opener and lift halfway; the door should stay in place.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Maintenance<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSchedule annual inspections for springs, cables, rollers, and the opener. Early detection prevents emergency repairs and extends door life.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Conclusion\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nBlocked tracks, misaligned sensors, worn springs, and faulty openers are common reasons behind a garage door that won\\u2019t close. Acting quickly can prevent injury, protect your home, and save you money in the long-term.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRegular maintenance and timely professional repairs ensure your garage door remains safe, reliable, and smooth-operating for years.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Ready To Repair Your Garage Door?\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nDon\\u2019t risk injury or property damage with a faulty garage door. Contact <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.google.com\\/maps?cid=8195650903324477361\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" style=\\\"\\\">Clark &amp; Sons Doors<\\/a> today for professional garage door repair, inspection, and maintenance.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"category_id\":\"5\",\"tag_id\":\"3\",\"published_at\":\"2026-02-16\",\"is_featured\":\"1\",\"image\":\"2923\",\"author\":\"10\",\"visibility\":\"Public\",\"password\":null,\"meta_title\":\"Garage Door Not Closing Issues and Fixes - Clark and Sons\",\"meta_keyword\":null,\"meta_description\":\"A garage door that won\\u2019t close may signal issues with sensors, tracks, or springs affecting safety and performance. Learn common causes and simple fixes easily.\",\"page_index\":\"on\",\"canonical_url\":null,\"format\":\"Standard\",\"status\":null,\"publish_status\":\"Draft\",\"created_by\":10,\"updated_by\":10,\"deleted_by\":null,\"created_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/18\",\"updated_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/31\",\"deleted_at\":null}', 10, 10, '2026-03-31 05:50:02', '2026-03-31 05:50:02', NULL);
INSERT INTO `updatelogs` (`id`, `tablename`, `table_primary_id`, `edit_log`, `created_by`, `updated_by`, `created_at`, `updated_at`, `deleted_at`) VALUES
(36, 'articles', '23', '{\"id\":23,\"title\":\"Expert Tips for Choosing the Right Loading Dock Doors for Your Business\",\"slug\":\"expert-tips-for-choosing-the-right-loading-dock-doors-for-your-business\",\"short_description\":\"Your loading dock doors are the heartbeat of your warehouse operations. Every shipment, delivery, and truck depends on doors that work reliably, efficiently, and safely.\",\"content\":\"<p>\\r\\nYour loading dock doors are the heartbeat of your warehouse operations. Every shipment, delivery, and truck depends on doors that work reliably, efficiently, and safely.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nChoosing the wrong doors can slow operations, increase energy costs, and create safety risks. The right doors improve workflow, energy efficiency, security, and long-term ROI.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nIn this guide, our team will guide you on choosing the right leading dock doors for your business.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Types of Loading Dock Doors\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nHere are the most common types of loading dock doors and what makes each one suitable for different business needs.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Sectional Overhead Doors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/commercial\\/commercial-sectional-garage-doors\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">\\r\\nSectional overhead doors<\\/a> consist of horizontal panels connected with hinges, which slide up along tracks and rest overhead when open.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nThey are the most common type for warehouses and distribution centers because they balance durability, insulation, and ease of use.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Key Features and Benefits:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Insulation Options: Panels can be filled with polyurethane or polystyrene to maintain climate control.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Durability: Steel panels resist impact and wear, while aluminum options are lighter and corrosion-resistant.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Customization: Heights, widths, and panel colours can be tailored to match your facility.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Operational Considerations:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Requires overhead clearance for the panels to rest when open.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Heavier doors need robust openers and torsion springs.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Maintenance includes lubricating hinges, rollers, and checking seals to prevent drafts.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Pros and Cons:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Pros: Quiet operation, insulated options, versatile for most docks.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Cons: Needs overhead space; panels can dent if struck by heavy equipment.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Rolling Doors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/commercial\\/commercial-rolling-doors\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">\\r\\nRolling doors<\\/a> coil into a compact roll above the opening, making them perfect for low-ceiling or limited overhead space. They are often used in urban facilities and high-traffic docks.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Key Features and Benefits:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Space Efficiency: Rolls into a compact coil, freeing overhead space.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Durable Construction: Steel slats handle high usage and resist warping.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Fast Operation: Opens quickly, reducing wait times for trucks.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Maintenance and Operational Tips:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate bearings regularly to prevent squeaks and jamming.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect steel slats for dents or rust that could interfere with rolling.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Consider pairing with a soft-close operator to reduce impact noise.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Pros and Cons:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Pros: High cycle rating, ideal for limited overhead, robust.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Cons: Limited insulation, can be noisy, may require heavier motors for larger openings.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  High-Speed Fabric Doors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/commercial\\/commercial-high-speed-fabric-doors\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">\\r\\nHigh-speed fabric doors<\\/a> are designed for efficiency. They open and close in seconds, minimizing air exchange, which is critical for climate-controlled or high-volume operations.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Key Features and Benefits:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Rapid Operation: Opens up to 100 inches per second in some models.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Energy Efficiency: Reduces heating\\/cooling loss by keeping the dock sealed.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Flexible Panels: Fabric panels absorb minor impacts without permanent damage.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Maintenance and Operational Tips:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect the fabric regularly for tears.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Keep sensors and photo-eyes clean to prevent automatic reversals.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Replace worn drive belts or motors to maintain speed.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Pros and Cons:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Pros: Energy-saving, ideal for cold storage, and reduces downtime.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Cons: Not suitable for heavy-duty industrial docks; fabric may wear faster in high-impact areas.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Sliding\\/Horizontal Doors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSliding doors move sideways instead of upward, which is useful when overhead space is restricted or when openings are oversized.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Key Features and Benefits:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Large Openings: Can cover wide or tall dock openings without overhead obstruction.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Durability: Steel or aluminum tracks handle heavy doors.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Smooth Operation: With proper track alignment, they slide easily even under heavy loads.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Maintenance and Operational Tips:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Check side tracks for warping or debris.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate rollers and track guides every 6 months.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Ensure proper clearance for forklifts and trucks.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Pros and Cons:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Pros: Perfect for oversized openings; requires no overhead space.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Cons: Needs side clearance; installation and alignment are critical.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Insulated Loading Dock Doors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nInsulated doors are designed to reduce energy costs, protect inventory, and maintain temperature inside warehouses. Insulation type, panel thickness, and sealing all impact efficiency.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Key Features and Benefits:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Thermal Efficiency: Panels reduce heat transfer and energy loss.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Noise Reduction: Insulated panels dampen operational noise.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Durability: Reinforced panels resist impact while maintaining energy efficiency.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Maintenance and Operational Tips:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Check seals and gaskets for cracks or warping.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Ensure insulation hasn\\u2019t compressed, especially in high-traffic docks.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Pair with fast operators to minimize air exchange during loading\\/unloading.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Pros and Cons:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Pros: Lower energy bills, climate control, quieter operation.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Cons: Higher initial cost; heavier doors need stronger motors.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Fire-Rated Doors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/commercial\\/commercial-fire-rated-rolling-doors-and-operators\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">\\r\\nFire-rated doors<\\/a> are mandatory in facilities handling flammable materials or where local regulations require fire containment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Key Features and Benefits:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Fire Protection: Slows fire spread, protecting employees and inventory.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Durable Materials: Steel and composite panels with tested fire resistance.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Code Compliance: Meets OSHA, NFPA, and local fire safety codes.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Maintenance and Operational Tips:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect yearly; any misalignment can compromise effectiveness.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Verify closing speed and sealing mechanism.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Test release mechanisms and sensors to ensure functionality.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><strong>Pros and Cons:<\\/strong><\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Pros: Life-saving, regulatory compliance, and reduces property damage.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Cons: Heavier, more expensive, professional installation required.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Factors to Consider When Choosing Loading Dock Doors\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nHere are a few things to keep in mind when selecting a loading dock door:\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Usage Frequency<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nHigh-traffic docks open thousands of times per year. Standard doors may wear out quickly, so high-cycle doors with reinforced rollers, heavy-duty tracks, and durable motors are ideal. For slower or seasonal operations, moderate-duty doors can save cost.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Climate Control Needs<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nTemperature-sensitive products require consistent conditions. Insulated doors help maintain interior temperatures, reduce energy costs, and prevent drafts, dust, and pests. Door seals and gaskets are also important.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Security Requirements<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nLoading dock doors serve as a first line of defence. Reinforced steel doors provide physical security, while access-controlled doors with keycards or smart sensors restrict entry.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Workflow Efficiency<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nDoor speed and reliability impact operational efficiency. High-speed doors reduce loading\\/unloading time, while doors that jam create bottlenecks and increase labour costs. Match door type to your facility\\u2019s workflow requirements.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Space Constraints<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>Check for:<\\/p>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Ceiling height: Sectional doors need overhead space; roll-up doors coil compactly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Side clearance: Sliding or horizontal doors require lateral space.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Obstructions: Overhead beams, lighting, or sprinklers can interfere with installation.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Compliance<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nEnsure doors meet fire codes, OSHA, and local building regulations. Fire-rated doors slow fire spread, and safety sensors or emergency release mechanisms may be legally required.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Budget and ROI<\\/h3>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nInitial cost is only part of the equation. You also need to consider:\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Maintenance costs: Frequent repairs or lubrication needs can add up.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Energy efficiency: Insulated doors can reduce heating\\/cooling bills.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Operational savings: Faster, reliable doors reduce labour costs and downtime.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Loading Dock Door Materials and Construction\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nThe material of your loading dock door impacts durability, maintenance, energy efficiency, and overall performance. Common materials for loading dock doors include:\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Steel<\\/h3>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Strength and security: Steel resists impact better than most materials.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Insulation options: Steel doors can include insulation panels for energy savings.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Durability: Coated steel resists rust, but unprotected panels may corrode in humid environments.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSteel is ideal for high-traffic docks or facilities storing heavy or valuable goods.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Aluminum<\\/h3>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Lightweight: Easier to operate and reduces strain on motors.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Corrosion-resistant: Ideal for humid or coastal environments.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Moderate-duty applications: Less durable than steel under frequent impact.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nAluminum works well for moderate-use docks or interior applications where weight and corrosion are concerns.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>Fiberglass<\\/h3>\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Low-maintenance: Resists rust, rot, and corrosion.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Light-transmitting panels: Allow natural light into the dock area, improving visibility.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Best for interior or low-traffic docks: Not as durable as steel for high-impact areas.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nFibreglass is ideal for warehouses that prioritize visibility, light, and minimal maintenance.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Conclusion\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nChoosing the right loading dock doors is critical for safety, efficiency, and profitability. Consider workflow, climate, security, materials, and long-term costs.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPair with professional installation and regular maintenance to maximize ROI, minimize downtime, and protect your workforce and inventory.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Need Help Choosing the Right Loading Dock Door?\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nContact <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.google.com\\/maps?cid=8195650903324477361\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">Clark &amp; Sons Doors<\\/a> today to schedule your consultation for expert guidance, professional installation, and ongoing maintenance.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"category_id\":\"12\",\"tag_id\":\"3\",\"published_at\":\"2026-02-25\",\"is_featured\":\"0\",\"image\":\"2924\",\"author\":\"10\",\"visibility\":\"Public\",\"password\":null,\"meta_title\":\"Expert Tips for Choosing Loading Dock Doors - Clark and Sons\",\"meta_keyword\":null,\"meta_description\":\"The right loading dock doors for your business impact safety, efficiency, and energy costs across daily operations. Discover expert tips to improve performance.\",\"page_index\":\"on\",\"canonical_url\":null,\"format\":\"Standard\",\"status\":null,\"publish_status\":\"Draft\",\"created_by\":10,\"updated_by\":10,\"deleted_by\":null,\"created_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/18\",\"updated_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/18\",\"deleted_at\":null}', 10, 10, '2026-03-31 06:01:40', '2026-03-31 06:01:40', NULL),
(37, 'articles', '22', '{\"id\":22,\"title\":\"Why Is My Garage Door Not Closing? Common Issues and Fixes\",\"slug\":\"garage-door-not-closing-issues-and-fixes\",\"short_description\":\"A garage door that refuses to close is a great inconvenience and a security risk. It leaves your home vulnerable to break-ins, wildlife, and weather damage.\",\"content\":\"<p>\\r\\nA garage door that refuses to close is a great inconvenience and a security risk. It leaves your home vulnerable to break-ins, wildlife, and weather damage. It also puts extra stress on the opener and door components, which can lead to costly repairs.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nIn this article, we\\u2019ll break down the most common reasons why your <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/\\\">garage door<\\/a> is not closing, and show you how to safely fix it.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  The Basics: Safety First\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nImportant safety rules to keep in mind when dealing with garage door problems include:\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Disconnect the opener before inspecting or performing any maintenance.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Never adjust springs or cables yourself. Mistakes can cause serious injury.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Limit DIY work to visual checks, cleaning, lubrication, and minor hardware tightening.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Common Reasons Why Your Garage Door Isn\'t Closing and How To Fix Them\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nA door that won\\u2019t close can result from several interconnected issues. Let\\u2019s examine them, how to spot them, and how to address them.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Obstructed or Dirty Tracks\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nTracks guide the door along its path. Any debris, dirt, or minor bends create friction that prevents the door from closing smoothly. Even a small pebble can stop a door mid-way. Over time, tracks can bend from repeated impact or improper installation, compounding the problem.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door stops mid-way or reverses without hitting the floor.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Scraping or grinding sounds during movement.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Uneven travel where one side moves faster than the other.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clear debris and dirt with a soft brush or cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect for small objects or minor bends.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Gently straighten minor bends using a rubber mallet. Never forcefully.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate rollers with silicone spray, avoiding the tracks themselves.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nFor severely bent tracks, repeated misalignment, or doors that come off the tracks, call Clark &amp; Sons technicians for professional realignment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Misaligned or Blocked Safety Sensors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nGarage doors have safety sensors to prevent accidents. They stop the door if something blocks the beam. If the sensors are misaligned, dirty, or loose, the door will refuse to close. Wiring can degrade, especially in older systems, preventing proper communication with the opener.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door reverses before reaching the floor.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door won\\u2019t move at all.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Sensor lights are dim, flickering, or off.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPersistent issues or damaged wiring should be handled by a technician to prevent accidents.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Broken or Worn Springs\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSprings balance the weight of the garage door. Torsion springs above the door or extension springs along the tracks allow smooth opening and closing. If they break or weaken, the door becomes heavy, difficult to control, or won\\u2019t move at all.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door closes unevenly, or one side lags.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Loud bangs or popping sounds.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door slams or stops abruptly.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Why DIY is risky:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSprings store enormous tension. Even slight mishandling can cause serious injury or property damage.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nOur trained technician will replace or adjust springs, ensuring proper tension and safe operation. They also inspect cables and drums during spring replacement to prevent related failures.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Malfunctioning Garage Door Opener\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nThe <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/residential\\/openers\\/\\\">garage door opener<\\/a> is the motor that drives the door. Motors wear out over time, especially in high-use systems. Chain or belt drives may loosen, gears can wear, and electrical components can fail.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door moves slowly, jerks, or stops midway.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door responds inconsistently to remote or wall control.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Unusual grinding, whining, or humming noises.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPersistent issues, unusual motor sounds, or partial movement usually indicate worn gears or motor failure. Technicians can replace parts or the entire opener to restore reliable operation.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Worn or Damaged Rollers\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRollers guide the door along the tracks. Over time, plastic rollers wear, steel rollers can rust, and bearings can seize. Misaligned rollers increase friction and strain the opener.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door sticks or shakes during movement.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Loud squeaking or grinding noises.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Uneven or partial closure.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nReplace rollers if damaged. Professionals ensure proper installation and alignment, which prevents noise, uneven movements, and premature opener wear.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Cable or Pulley Problems\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nCables lift the door while pulleys guide them. Frayed cables or misaligned pulleys disrupt smooth operation.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door closes unevenly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>One side of the door lags.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Sudden jerks or binding mid-travel.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nOnly a trained technician should replace or re-tension cables. Improper handling can result in dangerous door failure.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Door Off-Track\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nGarage doors can derail from their tracks due to impact, worn hardware, or misalignment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Door jams or tilts during closing.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Stops mid-way or doesn\\u2019t move at all.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Visible gaps between the door and track.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nStop using the door immediately. A technician will safely realign tracks and reposition the door, preventing serious accidents.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Preventive Maintenance for Smooth Closing\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRegular maintenance reduces the risk of your garage door refusing to close.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Maintenance Checklist:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate hinges, rollers, springs, and bearings every 6 months.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Clean tracks and remove debris.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect and tighten hardware: bolts, brackets, and screws.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Test and clean safety sensors monthly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Perform a balance test: disconnect the opener and lift halfway; the door should stay in place.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Maintenance<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSchedule annual inspections for springs, cables, rollers, and the opener. Early detection prevents emergency repairs and extends door life.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Conclusion\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nBlocked tracks, misaligned sensors, worn springs, and faulty openers are common reasons behind a garage door that won\\u2019t close. Acting quickly can prevent injury, protect your home, and save you money in the long-term.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRegular maintenance and timely professional repairs ensure your garage door remains safe, reliable, and smooth-operating for years.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Ready To Repair Your Garage Door?\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nDon\\u2019t risk injury or property damage with a faulty garage door. Contact <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.google.com\\/maps?cid=8195650903324477361\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" style=\\\"\\\">Clark &amp; Sons Doors<\\/a> today for professional garage door repair, inspection, and maintenance.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"category_id\":\"5\",\"tag_id\":\"3\",\"published_at\":\"2026-02-16\",\"is_featured\":\"0\",\"image\":\"2923\",\"author\":\"10\",\"visibility\":\"Public\",\"password\":null,\"meta_title\":\"Garage Door Not Closing Issues and Fixes - Clark and Sons\",\"meta_keyword\":null,\"meta_description\":\"A garage door that won\\u2019t close may signal issues with sensors, tracks, or springs affecting safety and performance. Learn common causes and simple fixes easily.\",\"page_index\":\"on\",\"canonical_url\":null,\"format\":\"Standard\",\"status\":null,\"publish_status\":\"Draft\",\"created_by\":10,\"updated_by\":10,\"deleted_by\":null,\"created_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/18\",\"updated_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/31\",\"deleted_at\":null}', 10, 10, '2026-03-31 08:08:39', '2026-03-31 08:08:39', NULL),
(38, 'articles', '22', '{\"id\":22,\"title\":\"Why Is My Garage Door Not Closing? Common Issues and Fixes\",\"slug\":\"garage-door-not-closing-issues-and-fixes\",\"short_description\":\"A garage door that refuses to close is a great inconvenience and a security risk. It leaves your home vulnerable to break-ins, wildlife, and weather damage.\",\"content\":\"<p>\\r\\nA garage door that refuses to close is a great inconvenience and a security risk. It leaves your home vulnerable to break-ins, wildlife, and weather damage. It also puts extra stress on the opener and door components, which can lead to costly repairs.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nIn this article, we\\u2019ll break down the most common reasons why your garage door is not closing and show you how to safely fix it.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  The Basics: Safety First\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nImportant safety rules to keep in mind when dealing with garage door problems include:\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Disconnect the opener before inspecting or performing any maintenance.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Never adjust springs or cables yourself. Mistakes can cause serious injury.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Limit DIY work to visual checks, cleaning, lubrication, and minor hardware tightening.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Common Reasons Why Your Garage Door Isn\'t Closing and How To Fix Them\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nA door that won\\u2019t close can result from several interconnected issues. Let\\u2019s examine them, how to spot them, and how to address them.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Obstructed or Dirty Tracks\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nTracks guide the door along its path. Any debris, dirt, or minor bends create friction that prevents the door from closing smoothly. Even a small pebble can stop a door mid-way. Over time, tracks can bend from repeated impact or improper installation, compounding the problem.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door stops mid-way or reverses without hitting the floor.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Scraping or grinding sounds during movement.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Uneven travel where one side moves faster than the other.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clear debris and dirt with a soft brush or cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect for small objects or minor bends.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Gently straighten minor bends using a rubber mallet. Never forcefully.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate rollers with silicone spray, avoiding the tracks themselves.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nFor severely bent tracks, repeated misalignment, or doors that come off the tracks, call Clark &amp; Sons technicians for professional realignment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Misaligned or Blocked Safety Sensors\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nGarage doors have safety sensors to prevent accidents. They stop the door if something blocks the beam. If the sensors are misaligned, dirty, or loose, the door will refuse to close. Wiring can degrade, especially in older systems, preventing proper communication with the opener.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door reverses before reaching the floor.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door won\\u2019t move at all.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Sensor lights are dim, flickering, or off.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPersistent issues or damaged wiring should be handled by a technician to prevent accidents.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Broken or Worn Springs\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSprings balance the weight of the garage door. Torsion springs above the door or extension springs along the tracks allow smooth opening and closing. If they break or weaken, the door becomes heavy, difficult to control, or won\\u2019t move at all.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door closes unevenly, or one side lags.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Loud bangs or popping sounds.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door slams or stops abruptly.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Why DIY is risky:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSprings store enormous tension. Even slight mishandling can cause serious injury or property damage.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nOur trained technician will replace or adjust springs, ensuring proper tension and safe operation. They also inspect cables and drums during spring replacement to prevent related failures.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Malfunctioning Garage Door Opener\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nThe <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/residential\\/openers\\/\\\">garage door opener<\\/a> is the motor that drives the door. Motors wear out over time, especially in high-use systems. Chain or belt drives may loosen, gears can wear, and electrical components can fail.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door moves slowly, jerks, or stops midway.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>The door responds inconsistently to remote or wall control.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Unusual grinding, whining, or humming noises.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nPersistent issues, unusual motor sounds, or partial movement usually indicate worn gears or motor failure. Technicians can replace parts or the entire opener to restore reliable operation.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Worn or Damaged Rollers\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRollers guide the door along the tracks. Over time, plastic rollers wear, steel rollers can rust, and bearings can seize. Misaligned rollers increase friction and strain the opener.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door sticks or shakes during movement.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Loud squeaking or grinding noises.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Uneven or partial closure.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Fix Steps:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Clean the sensor lenses gently with a soft cloth.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Check alignment: sensors must face each other directly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Tighten any loose mounting brackets.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Help:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nReplace rollers if damaged. Professionals ensure proper installation and alignment, which prevents noise, uneven movements, and premature opener wear.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Cable or Pulley Problems\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nCables lift the door while pulleys guide them. Frayed cables or misaligned pulleys disrupt smooth operation.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>The door closes unevenly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>One side of the door lags.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Sudden jerks or binding mid-travel.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nOnly a trained technician should replace or re-tension cables. Improper handling can result in dangerous door failure.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h3>\\r\\n  Door Off-Track\\r\\n<\\/h3>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nGarage doors can derail from their tracks due to impact, worn hardware, or misalignment.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Signs to watch for:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Door jams or tilts during closing.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Stops mid-way or doesn\\u2019t move at all.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Visible gaps between the door and track.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Solution:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nStop using the door immediately. A technician will safely realign tracks and reposition the door, preventing serious accidents.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Preventive Maintenance for Smooth Closing\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRegular maintenance reduces the risk of your garage door refusing to close.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>DIY Maintenance Checklist:<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<ul>\\r\\n  <li>Lubricate hinges, rollers, springs, and bearings every 6 months.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Clean tracks and remove debris.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Inspect and tighten hardware: bolts, brackets, and screws.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Test and clean safety sensors monthly.<\\/li>\\r\\n  <li>Perform a balance test: disconnect the opener and lift halfway; the door should stay in place.<\\/li>\\r\\n<\\/ul>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n<strong>Professional Maintenance<\\/strong>\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nSchedule annual inspections for springs, cables, rollers, and the opener. Early detection prevents emergency repairs and extends door life.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Conclusion\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nBlocked tracks, misaligned sensors, worn springs, and faulty openers are common reasons behind a garage door that won\\u2019t close. Acting quickly can prevent injury, protect your home, and save you money in the long-term.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nRegular maintenance and timely professional repairs ensure your garage door remains safe, reliable, and smooth-operating for years.\\r\\n<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<h2>\\r\\n  Ready To Repair Your Garage Door?\\r\\n<\\/h2>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>\\r\\nDon\\u2019t risk injury or property damage with a faulty garage door. Contact <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.google.com\\/maps?cid=8195650903324477361\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\" style=\\\"\\\">Clark &amp; Sons Doors<\\/a> today for <a href=\\\"https:\\/\\/clarkandsonsdoors.com\\/\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">professional garage door repair<\\/a>, inspection, and maintenance.\\r\\n<\\/p>\",\"category_id\":\"5\",\"tag_id\":\"3\",\"published_at\":\"2026-02-16\",\"is_featured\":\"0\",\"image\":\"2923\",\"author\":\"10\",\"visibility\":\"Public\",\"password\":null,\"meta_title\":\"Garage Door Not Closing Issues and Fixes - Clark and Sons\",\"meta_keyword\":null,\"meta_description\":\"A garage door that won\\u2019t close may signal issues with sensors, tracks, or springs affecting safety and performance. Learn common causes and simple fixes easily.\",\"page_index\":\"on\",\"canonical_url\":null,\"format\":\"Standard\",\"status\":null,\"publish_status\":\"Draft\",\"created_by\":10,\"updated_by\":10,\"deleted_by\":null,\"created_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/18\",\"updated_at\":\"2026\\/03\\/31\",\"deleted_at\":null}', 10, 10, '2026-04-01 09:08:11', '2026-04-01 09:08:11', NULL),
